ce:section.ce:para:
In the era of technological advancement, nanoparticles-based drug delivery strategies have surfaced as a potent stratagem for many fatal clinical ailments including cancer, cardiovascular diseases, diabetes, etc. [75]. Many novel nanoparticle-based strategies have surfaced that have shown great potential as a prominent drug delivery methodology [76]. In this regard, Xia et al. fabricated meso-tetrakis (1-methylpyridinium-4-yl) porphyrin (MTMP) encapsulated injectable hydrogel systems composed of glycol chitosan (CS) and di benzaldehyde-terminated telechelic poly(ethylene glycol). Compared to MTMP, the modified hydrogels exhibited more efficient delivery of MTMP, demonstrated singlet oxygen in the presence of similar laser irradiation conditions, longer tumor retention, and increased fluorescence intensity [73]. In another study, Ahlen et al. developed lenses composed of polyvinyl alcohol (PVA)-based hydrogels co-loaded with CS-poly (acrylic acid) nanoparticles (CS-PAA NPs) and cellulose nanocrystals (CNs) for delivery of ophthalmic drugs in a controlled manner. The formulations demonstrated the disintegration of NPs in lysozyme (0.2 mM) due to cleavage of the CS chains via hydrolysis. The leaching was efficiently prevented due to in-situ gelation between the CS-PAA NPs and CNs [77]. In the field of fluorescent nanoparticles-based drug delivery strategies, Yue et al. synthesized thermos-sensitive graphene quantum dots encapsulated with dextran- poly (N-isopropyl acrylamide), forming GQD-DP polymeric complex. The complex polymeric systems exhibited superior biocompatibility and biodegradability with asymmetric appearance and porous structure. The polymeric complexes demonstrated sustained and enhanced drug release with a thermo-responsive behaviour due to the polymeric coat. The GQD-DP-treated groups exhibited no inflammation with substantial stromal cell permeation, signifying that the synthesized polymeric formulation can be an efficient platform for pain management with no toxicity to nerves [78]. Moreover, in a separate study, Men et al. developed nanostructured polymeric dots conjugated thermosensitive hydrogels with improved theranostic applications, including triple activities: photoacoustic, computed tomography, and fluorescence imaging-guided chemo- and photo-thermal synergistic therapeutic platform against tumour therapy [74]. Here, a multifunctional indacenodithiophene (IDT)-BTzTD polymer dots (Pdots) was utilized for developing Pdots–DOX–iohexol@hydrogel(Pdots@hydrogel) nanosystem. The designed nano platform was also analyzed for Realtime fluorescence and computed tomography signals, pre and post-administration for various treatment groups at specific intervals (
                        Fig. 4
                        ). The conjugated nanostructures exhibited superior biodegradability, bright photoacoustic/computed tomography (CT)/fluorescence signals, robust NIR absorption, and higher tumor excision effect.

In a separate study, Zhang et al. reported the biosensing and bioimaging of extracellular lactate through Nile blue-functionalized-QDs (NBQD) loaded hydrogel-mediated fluorescent probes. Notably, the surface-engineered QD-hydrogel showed extensive selectivity towards the lactate over amino acids, common metallic ions, and other smaller molecules that extensively co-occur in the biological system. Furthermore, the destabilized NBQD-hydrogel encapsulated the isolated carcinogenic cells when self-linked into the hydrogel system and thus precisely detected and imaged the metabolism of extracellular lactate [118]. Further, Zhao et al. fabricated dual-charged pH-sensitive nanosized hydrogel with green fluorescence, which acted as bio-probes for active tumor targeting and bio-imaging of cancerous cells. The hydrogel NPs were developed through an emulsion-free copolymerization technique that comprised polystyrene as core material and the shell segment composed of ar-vinyl benzyl) trimethylammonium (a strong positive electrolyte) and acrylic acid (a weak negative electrolyte). Further, these hybrid hydrogels were conjugated with folic acid for active targeting. Results demonstrated that the hydrogel system exhibited targeted anticancer activity by inhibiting tumor aggregation and also showed quick cellular imaging of cancerous cells [119]. In another study, Key et al. modified hydrogels with polymeric (PLGA and PEG- dimethacrylate)-based nanocarriers using one-step synthesis and further loaded with ultra-small super-paramagnetic iron oxide NPs (USPIOs) and Rhodamine B dye (
                        Fig. 11

                        ). The dye showed pH-depended release and significantly augmented under acidic circumstances. Moreover, it was noticed that the MRI relaxivity increased (up to ∼ 5 times larger) with the payload of SPIONs in hydrogels, and thus can be considered for theranostic application in anti-angiogenic and vascular bio-imaging [120]. Moreover, Khabibullin et al. prepared a multifunctional hydrogel system using cellulose nanocrystals and graphene QDs with efficient mechanical properties. Owed to their shear-thinning performance, the hydrogels were utilized in 3D printing as an injectable component. In addition, the hydrogels demonstrated fluorescence and exhibited anisotropic nanofibrillar assembly [121]. The utility of advanced fabrication techniques like 3D printing has been an attractive option to be explored for designing unique hydrogels encapsulating fluorescent nanoprobes for bioimaging applications. However, very limited studies have been reported where radionuclide tagging has been involved with fluorescent probes. This strategy can give multifunctionality to the designed system and at the same time can be used as a single probe for optical signals and radioactive signals. Efforts are being made to further enhance the sensitivity of designed hybrid hydrogels for widespread utility in biomedical applications.

Up recently, upconversion nanoparticles (UCNPs) have gained considerable attraction due to their superiority over QDs and organic dyes [122,123]. UCNPs have been explored for their utility in bioimaging due to minimal autofluorescence, great detection sensitivity, and high penetration depth [124]. In this regard, Li et al. reported the potential synergistic activity of DOX-loaded gelatin hydrogels conjugated with upconversion NPs (NaLuF4:Er3+, Yb3+) and nano graphene oxide (DOX-GT/UCNP-NGO) in cancer therapy and up-conversion luminescence imaging. DOX-GT/UCNP-NGO hydrogels released the DOX through laser irradiation or within the tumor microenvironment, and further, the efficacy of chemotherapy was improved by enhanced through chemo-photothermal synergistic effects (
                        Figure 12

                        ). Results of the in vitro studies showed that the DOX-GT/UCNP-NGO hydrogels exhibited potential photothermal effects and exceptional tumor-killing efficacy. In addition, in vivo antitumor studies also showed similar findings for DOX-GT/UCNP-NGO hydrogels in synergistic antitumor efficiency [125].
